[Student "S"]
{Partner's 3\D bid shows a 5-card suit and is forcing to game. While 5\D is possibly the best contract your double \H stopper should sway you to 3NT instead. This is the old "9 tricks are easier than 11" principle.

South plays 3NT. As expected, West attacks in his \H suit.

Winner List: \S = 2 : \H = 2 : \D = 0 : \C = 2 :: Total = 6

Even if East holds both black Queens, (not likely), you can only finesse your way to 8 tricks. Since you need 9 tricks you must establish the \D suit.

If West holds both the \DA and \DK then you are going down, because they will win the race to establish \Hs before you can establish \Ds. 

But when the \DA and \DK are in different hands you have a good chance for success; it depends on East having no \H at the time he takes his \D winner. 

So you should hold up on the first \H trick and win the second. If West started with 6 \Hs then East will be out. So whether he wins his \D trick first or second he still won't be able to continue \Hs.

After your hold up East has no \Hs. If he takes the first \D trick he will have to lead another suit. You will still have a \H stopper for when West wins <b>HIS</b> \D trick.

On the other hand, if West takes the first \D trick he can certainly drive out your last \H stopper. But then, when East takes <b>HIS</b> \D winner he will have no \H.

Finally, if West had only a 5-card \H suit, good defense would beat you. But they have to be sure East wins the first \D trick, and they might slip up. }
[Play "W"]HQ

